sections.content_markdown:
These properties control how items are positioned within their individual grid cells.

:::code[language="css" title="Items Alignment Properties"]
.grid {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: repeat(3, 200px);
  grid-template-rows: repeat(2, 150px);
  gap: 10px;

  /* Horizontal alignment within cells */
  justify-items: start | end | center | stretch;

  /* Vertical alignment within cells */
  align-items: start | end | center | stretch;
}
:::

:::definition[title="Alignment Values"]
- `start` - Align to the start edge of the cell
- `end` - Align to the end edge of the cell
- `center` - Center within the cell
- `stretch` - Fill the entire cell (default)
:::

:::code[language="html" title="Visual Examples"]
<style>
.grid {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: repeat(3, 150px);
  grid-template-rows: repeat(2, 100px);
  gap: 10px;
  background: #f0f0f0;
}

.item {
  background: #3b82f6;
  padding: 10px;
  color: white;
}

/* Items shrink to content size and align */
.grid-start {
  justify-items: start;
  align-items: start;
}

.grid-center {
  justify-items: center;
  align-items: center;
}

.grid-end {
  justify-items: end;
  align-items: end;
}
</style>

<div class="grid grid-center">
  <div class="item">Centered</div>
  <div class="item">In Cell</div>
  <div class="item">Content</div>
</div>
:::

:::pitfall[title="stretch vs Fixed Dimensions"]
WRONG expectation:
```css
.grid {
  justify-items: stretch; /* Default */
  align-items: stretch;   /* Default */
}

.item {
  width: 50px;  /* These override stretch! */
  height: 30px;
}
```

RIGHT understanding:
```css
/* stretch only works when items don't have 
   explicit width/height set */
.item {
  /* No width/height = stretches to fill cell */
}
```

WHY:
When items have explicit dimensions, they can't stretch. The item uses its specified size and alignment positions it within the cell.
:::

sections.code_snippet:
.grid {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: repeat(3, 1fr);
  justify-items: center;
  align-items: center;
}

sections.content_markdown:
The `place-items` property combines `align-items` and `justify-items` into one declaration.

:::code[language="css" title="place-items Syntax"]
.grid {
  /* Shorthand: align-items / justify-items */
  place-items: center end;

  /* Equivalent to: */
  align-items: center;
  justify-items: end;
}

/* Single value applies to both */
.grid-centered {
  place-items: center;

  /* Equivalent to: */
  align-items: center;
  justify-items: center;
}
:::

:::realworld[title="Perfect Centering with Grid"]
The easiest way to center anything:

```css
.container {
  display: grid;
  place-items: center;
  min-height: 100vh;
}
```

```html
<div class="container">
  <div class="card">
    Perfectly centered card!
  </div>
</div>
```

This is often simpler than flexbox centering because you don't need to set both `justify-content` and `align-items`—`place-items: center` handles both axes.
:::

:::tabs
## Cards Grid [css]
```css
/* Cards centered in their cells */
.card-grid {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fill, minmax(250px, 1fr));
  gap: 24px;
  place-items: center stretch;
}
```

## Icon Grid [css]
```css
/* Icons centered both ways */
.icon-grid {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: repeat(4, 60px);
  grid-template-rows: repeat(4, 60px);
  gap: 8px;
  place-items: center;
}

.icon {
  width: 32px;
  height: 32px;
}
```
:::

:::checkpoint[question="What does place-items: end center do?" hint="First value is align-items, second is justify-items"]
It sets `align-items: end` (vertical - items at bottom of cells) and `justify-items: center` (horizontal - items centered in cells).
:::

sections.code_snippet:
/* Center everything perfectly */
.grid {
  display: grid;
  place-items: center;
  min-height: 100vh;
}

sections.content_markdown:
These properties position the entire grid tracks within the container—useful when the grid is smaller than its container.

:::code[language="css" title="Content Alignment"]
.grid {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: repeat(3, 100px); /* 300px total */
  width: 600px; /* Container is larger than grid */

  /* Position the grid horizontally */
  justify-content: start | end | center | 
                   space-between | space-around | space-evenly;

  /* Position the grid vertically */
  align-content: start | end | center | 
                 space-between | space-around | space-evenly;
}
:::

:::definition[title="Content Alignment Values"]
- `start` - Pack tracks at the start
- `end` - Pack tracks at the end
- `center` - Center the tracks
- `space-between` - Even space between tracks, none at edges
- `space-around` - Even space around each track
- `space-evenly` - Equal space between tracks and edges
:::

:::code[language="css" title="Visual Example"]
.container {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: repeat(3, 100px);
  grid-template-rows: repeat(2, 80px);
  width: 500px;
  height: 300px;
  background: #e5e7eb;

  /* Center the 300px grid in 500px container */
  justify-content: center;

  /* Distribute rows in 300px height container */
  align-content: space-between;
}
:::

:::pitfall[title="Content Alignment Has No Effect"]
WRONG:
```css
.grid {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr 1fr; /* Takes full width! */
  justify-content: center; /* No effect */
}
```

RIGHT:
```css
.grid {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: 100px 100px 100px; /* Fixed widths */
  justify-content: center; /* Now works! */
}
```

WHY:
`justify-content` only works when there's extra space. If columns use `fr` units or percentages that fill the container, there's no space to distribute.
:::

:::realworld[title="Footer with Spaced Sections"]
```css
.footer {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: repeat(4, max-content);
  justify-content: space-between;
  padding: 40px;
}

.footer-section {
  /* Each section sizes to its content */
  /* space-between distributes them evenly */
}
```
:::

